			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Ok, I can understand bout the confusion about Mages in the new D&amp;D rules wearing armor. The thing you have to take note of is that The &quot;Armored Mage&quot; is a prestige class that is an exception to the rules. Now, a normal mage can wear armor, but he takes HEAVY Arcane Spell Failure Checks to it. Say he is wearing leather armor, well he gets a spell failure of 20%. So what he does is proclaim that he wants to cast a spell, and then rolls two ten sided dice. If the total comes up from 1-20, then his spell failed. Now say he wants to use a Wooden shield and Leather armor. You would add the failure checks together which would come out to like 30% I beleive. That is how mages can wear armor, although I doubt very seriously.... they would due to the check failures
				</font>
			</td>

